{"cursor":"5208","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\nThe 'orbital speed' of a body, generally a planet, a natural satellite, an\nartificial satellite, or a multiple star, is the speed at which it orbits\naround the barycenter of a system, usually around a more massive body. It can\nbe used to refer to either the mean orbital speed, the average speed as it\ncompletes an orbit, or instantaneous orbital speed, the speed at a particular\npoint in its orbit.\n\nThe orbital speed at any position in the orbit can be computed from the distance\nto the central body at that position, and the specific orbital energy, which is\nindependent of position: the kinetic energy is the total energy minus the\npotential energy.\n","linknr":304,"url":"Orbital_speed","recorded":1362568945,"links":51,"instances":["astronomy","geometry"],"pdf":[],"categories":["Orbits"],"headings":["Radial trajectories","Transverse orbital speed","Mean orbital speed","See also","References"],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/a/8/5/a852d6da080d216ddb205b6c1acb9e3b.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/0/8/4/0849e12f19e9c83c0774b42dee97c668.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/a/0/e/a0e18cd14277633b1e7d16945672ac28.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/1/2/d/12de7673992b1735e29cdd211851fa05.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/c/d/3/cd322a0269b30952befe1f9ae7972bcc.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/7/4/b/74b8eddf4b37de80c7c8eed1b64e46fc.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/1/9/6/196332fee594fecf37baf3358a772f70.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/a/d/1/ad13eaeb30958e516ca20fdf2ef6ac89.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/9/2/1/92112b17b9b6d8eee0a6e42ee240214b.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/c/4/f/c4f4c3516ae8626abc95626b5686a2b1.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/6/5/5/655e6e2dafb5ac839c51dd6c7f7493b5.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/5/4/f/54f7c0c46e004968dd496cc4aa2b4f76.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/math/